question:
Problem 2: Comment on the chemical shifts of these three compounds and suggest whether there is a worthwhile correlation with \( \mathrm{p}{K}_{\mathrm{a}} \) . Media:
Compound\( {\delta }_{\mathrm{H}} \) ,p.p.m.pKa
CH3NO24.3310
\( {\mathrm{{CH}}}_{2}{\left( {\mathrm{{NO}}}_{2}\right) }_{2} \)6.104
\( \mathrm{{CH}}{\left( {\mathrm{{NO}}}_{2}\right) }_{3} \)7.520
Purpose of the problem: Simple correlation of structure and chemical shift.
answer: Suggested solution: The nitro group is a strongly electron-withdrawing group and would be expected to remove electron shielding from neighbouring hydrogen atoms. A \( {\mathrm{{CH}}}_{3} \) group would normally come at about 1.2 p.p.m. so one nitro group has shifted this downfield by about 3 p.p.m. The second adds less than 2 p.p.m. and the third only just 1.4 p.p.m. These diminishing effects are much smaller than the effects on \( \mathrm{p}{K}_{\mathrm{a}} \)
column4: but in the same direction. There is a kind of correlation showing that removing electrons from a \( \mathrm{C} - \mathrm{H} \) bond makes it more acidic and also increases the chemical shift."

question: Problem 3: One isomer of dimethoxybenzoic acid has the \( {}^{1}\mathrm{H} \) NMR spectrum \( {\delta }_{\mathrm{H}} \) (p.p.m.) 3.85 (6H,s), 6.63 (1H,t,J 2Hz),7.17 (2H,d,J 2Hz) and one isomer of coumalic acid has the \( {}^{1}\mathrm{H} \) NMR spectrum \( {\delta }_{H} \) (p.p.m.) 6.41 (1H,d,J 10 Hz),7.82 (1H,dd,J 2,10 Hz),and 8.51 (1H,d, \( \mathrm{J}2\mathrm{\;{Hz}} \) ). In each case,which isomer is it? The substituents on bonds sticking into the centre of the rings can be on any carbon atom. Media: `` Purpose of the problem: First steps in using coupling to decide structure.
answer: Suggested solution: The coupling constants in the first spectrum are all too small to be between Hs on neighbouring Cs and there is symmetry in the molecule. There is only one structure that answers these criteria. The compound is 3
column3: 5-dimethoxybenzoic acid. The other coupling is \( 2\mathrm{\;{Hz}} \) and this must be meta coupling. There are two structures that might be right. In fact
column4: the first is correct and you might have worked that out by the very large chemical shift - almost in the aldehyde region - of the isolated proton with only a \( 2\mathrm{\;{Hz}} \) coupling. This is on - alkene carbon bonded to oxygen in the first structure but on a simple alkene carbon in the second. question: Problem 4: Assign the NMR spectra of this compound (assign means say which signal belongs to which atom) and justify your assignments. Media: `CC1=CC(C)(C)OC(=O)C1` Purpose of the problem: Effectice in the interpretation of real NMR spectra - this is harder than if the spectra have already Eth measured.
answer: Suggested solution: There is no coupling in the proton NMR spectrum
column4: but you should The aberration chierical shifts and estimate the number of protons in each signal from the integration. \( {\delta }_{\mathrm{H}} \) (p.p.m.) 1.4 (6H)
column7: and 5.5 (1H). The peak at 7.25 p.p.m. is \( {\mathrm{{CHCl}}}_{3} \) impurity in the \( {\mathrm{{CDCl}}}_{3} \) solvent. Media: `CC1=CC(C)(C)OC(=O)C1.[13CH4].[13CH4].[13CH4]` This is enough to assign the spectrum but we should check that the chemical shifts are right too
column8: and they are. The carbon spectrum is more familiar to you from Chapter 3 and you will remember that regration means little here. There are three peaks in the \( 0 - {50} \) p.p.m. region corresponding to the The thyl group on the alkene
column10: and the pair of methyls on the same carbon atom. The 11:1 triplet at 77 p.p.m. is the solvent \( {\mathrm{{CDCl}}}_{3} \) . The other signal in the \( {50} - {100} \) p.p.m. region must be the carbon next to oxygen \( \left( {{\mathrm{{Me}}}_{2}\mathrm{{CO}}}\right) \) . The two signals in the 100-150 p.p.m. region are the two Errions of the alkene and the very small peak above 150 p.p.m. must be the carbonyl group. No further assignment is necessary."

answer: Suggested solution: Redrawing the molecules with all hydrogens showing probably helps at this stage
column3: though you will not do this for long. The spectrum of 1-nitrobutane can be assigned by integration and splitting pattern without even looking at the chemical shifts! Just counting the number of neighbours and adding one gives the multiplicity of the signals and leads to the assignment in the frame. It is equally valid to start with the chemical shift

question: Problem 6: The reaction below was expected to give product \( 6\mathrm{\;A} \) and did indeed give a product with the correct molecular formula by mass spectrum. The \( {}^{1}\mathrm{H} \) NMR spectrum of the product was however: \( {\delta }_{\mathrm{H}} \) (p.p.m.) 1.27 (6H,s),1.70 (4H,m),2.88 (2H,m),5.4-6.1 (2H,broad s, exchanges with \( {\mathrm{D}}_{2}\mathrm{O} \) ), 7.0-7.5 (3H,m). Though the detail is missing from this spectrum,how can you already tell that this is not the compound expected? Media: `CC1(C)CCCC2=C(C=CC=C2)NC1=O.CC1(C)CCCC2=C(C=CC=C2)NC1=O.[B].[B].[B].[B]` Purpose of the problem: To show that it is helpful to predict the NMR spectrum of an expected product provided that the structure is rejected if the spectrum is 'wrong'.
answer: Suggested solution: The spectrum is all wrong. There are only three aromatic Hs (7.0-7.5 p.p.m.)
column3: not the four expected. There are two exchanging hydrogens
column5: and not the one expected. The only thing 3. is as expected is the chain of three \( {\mathrm{{CH}}}_{2} \) groups. You could not be expected to find the right structure
column6: which is actually an amide with a new carbocyclic ring. Media: `CC/1(C)CCCC2=C1C=CC=C2C(=O)N.CC/1(C)CCCC2=C(C=CC=C2)\C1=N/O.CC.[CH3-].[Y]` This surprising result was reported by B. Amit and A. Hassner
column9: 932. The expected reaction was the Beckmann rearrangement (Chapter 37) but what actually happened was a Beckmann fragmentation (Chapter 38) followed by an intramolecular Friedel-Crafts alkylation (Chapter 22)."

question: Problem 8: A nitration product \( \left( {{\mathrm{C}}_{8}{\mathrm{H}}_{11}{\mathrm{\;N}}_{3}{\mathrm{O}}_{2}}\right) \) of this pyridine has been isolated which has a nitro \( \left( {\mathrm{{NO}}}_{2}\right) \) group somewhere on the molecule. From the \( {90}\mathrm{{MHz}}{}^{1}\mathrm{H} \) NMR spectrum,deduce whether the nitro group is (a) on the ring, (b) on the NH nitrogen atom, or (c) on the aliphatic side chain and then exactly where it is. Give a full analysis of the spectrum. Media: `CCCN(C1=NC=CC=C1)N(Cl)Cl.CC(CNC1=NC=CC=C1)N(Cl)Cl.CCCNC1=NC(=CC=C1)[N+](=O)[O-]` Purpose of the problem: Practice at interpretation of high-field NMR spectra. More complex problems can be solved reasonably easily.
answer: Suggested solution: Checking the integral will deal with that problem. The propyl side chain is still there with a \( {\mathrm{{CH}}}_{3} \) triplet
column4: and a \( {\mathrm{{CH}}}_{2} \) triplet with a large chemical shift. The broad signal at \( {\delta }_{\mathrm{H}}{5.9} \) p.p.m. is typical of an NH group so no reaction has happened there. The small signal - less than a quarter of a proton - at 7.2 p.p.m. cannot be part of the molecule and must be \( {\mathrm{{CHCl}}}_{3} \) . The remaining signals in the aromatic region at 6.3
column6: and 9.1 p.p.m. must be three protons on the pyridine ring. The nitro group has replaced one of the original four and is somewhere on the pyridine ring. These are the possibilities. Media: `CCCNC1=NC=CC(=C1)N.CCCNC1=NC=CC=C1N.CCCNC1=NC=CC=C1.CCCNC1=NC=CC=C1` The most significant feature of the aromatic region is a proton at very large chemical shift (9.1 p.p.m.) with no coupling to speak of (there might be some long-range coupling). This proton has no neighbours and that rules out the 3-nitro and 6-nitro compounds. If you check in tables you will see that protons on carbons next to nitrogen (C2 and C6) in pyridine have very large shifts as you would expect from their aldehyde-like nature. The nitro group also increases the shifts of protons on neighbouring carbon atoms. The compound must be 5-nitro and the spectrum can be assigned like this. Media: `CCN(CC)C1=C(N=C(C(=C1[R1])N(CC)CC[Y11])N(CC)CC[R13])N(CC)CC.C(CNC1=NC=C(C=N1)[N+](=O)[O-])C[R19].CCCNC1=NC=C(C=N1)[N+](=O)[O-].CC` The coupling in the side chain is all about \( 7\mathrm{\;{Hz}} \) as expected and that between \( \mathrm{C}3 \) and \( \mathrm{C}4 \) in the pyridine ring is somewhat larger also as expected for an aromatic ring. The smaller chemical shift of the proton at \( \mathrm{C}3 \) occurs because it is not affected by the nitro group but it is affected by electron donation from the amine nitrogen atom."

question: Problem 9: The natural product bullatenone was isolated in the 1950s from a New Zealand myrtle and assigned the structure 9A. Then compound 9A was synthesized and found not to be identical with natural bullatenone. Predict the expected \( {}^{1}\mathrm{H} \) NMR spectrum of 9A. Given the full spectroscopic data available nowadays, but not in the 1950s, say why 9A is definitely wrong and suggest a better structure for builatenone. Media: `CC1COC(=CC1=O)[Pb]` 9A alleged bullatenone Spectra of bullatenone: Mass spectrum: \( \mathrm{m}/\mathrm{z}{188}\left( {{10}\% }\right) \) (high resolution confirms \( {\mathrm{C}}_{12}{\mathrm{H}}_{12}{\mathrm{O}}_{2} \) ), 105 (20%), 102 (100%), and 77 (20%). Infrared: 1604 and \( {1705}{\mathrm{\;{cm}}}^{-1} \) . \( {}^{1}\mathrm{H} \) NMR: \( {\delta }_{\mathrm{H}} \) (p.p.m.) 1.45 \( \left( {6\mathrm{H},\mathrm{s}}\right) ,{5.82}\left( {1\mathrm{H},\mathrm{s}}\right) ,{7.35}\left( {3\mathrm{H},\mathrm{m}}\right) \) ,and 7.68(2H,m). Purpose of the problem: Detecting wrong structures is fun and teaches us to be alert to what the spectra are telling us rather than what we expect.
answer: Suggested solution: The mass spectrum and infrared are all right for structure 9A but the NMR shows at once that bullatenone cannot be \( 9\mathrm{\;A} \) . There is indeed a monosubstituted benzene ring (the \( 2\mathrm{H} \) and \( 3\mathrm{H} \) signals in the aromatic region confirm this) but the aliphatic protons consist of a \( 6\mathrm{H} \) signal
column4: and a \( 1\mathrm{H} \) singlet in the alkene region at 5.82 p.p.m. The fragments we have are \( \mathrm{{Ph}} \)
column6: and \( {\mathrm{{CMe}}}_{2} \) groups and an alkene with one \( \mathrm{H} \) on it. That adds up to \( {\mathrm{C}}_{12}{\mathrm{H}}_{12}\mathrm{O} \) and leaves only one oxygen atom to fit in. There must still be a ring or else there will be too few hydrogen atoms and the ring is five-membered (just try other possibilities yourself). There are three basic rings we can choose and each can have the phenyl group on either end of the double bond making six possibilities in all. Media: `CC1(C)C(=CC(=O)N1[O-])[Hg].CC1(C)C(=CC(=O)N1[O-])[Hg].CC1(C)C(=CC(=O)N1[O-])[Hg].CC1(C)C(=CC(=O)N1[O-])[Hg].CC1(C)C=C([N+](=O)N1[O-])[Hg].CC1(C)C=C([N+](=O)N1[O-])[Hg].[Hg].[Hg]` The last four are all esters (cyclic esters or lactones) and they would have IR carbonyl stretches at higher frequency in the \( {1745} - {1780}{\mathrm{\;{cm}}}^{-1} \) range. The hydrogen on the alkene cannot be on the same carbon atom as the oxygen or it would be at a very large shift indeed whereas it is close to the 'normal' alkene shift of 5.25 p.p.m. For 9C we could estimate 5.25 + 0.64 p.p.m. for O
column9: a long way from the observed 5.82 p.p.m. Structure 9B is correct and the spectra can be assigned. Compound \( 9\mathrm{\;B} \) was synthesized and proved identical to natural bullatenone. Media: `CC1(C)C(=O)C(=C(C2=C([2H])C([2H])=C([2H])C([2H])=C2[2H])O1)[R2].CC.CC.CC.CC.CC.[B].[B].[B].[B].[B].[B]`"
